# Implementation Plan — Database Query Optimization via Indexing

This plan outlines the strategy to optimize SplitSmart's database performance by defining targeted database indexes in Mongoose models. To prove the efficacy of these indexes in numbers, we will write a specialized local benchmark script that seeds mock data, measures query execution latency (before vs. after indexing) using MongoDB's `executionStats`, and outputs concrete performance numbers.

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Production Context & Resource Tradeoffs:**
> Indexing significantly improves query speed (read operations) but introduces a slight write overhead (inserts, updates, deletes) because MongoDB must rebuild index trees. For a group expense splitter where reads (dashboard loading, viewing expenses, loading chat history) vastly outnumber writes, this is an excellent trade-off.

> [!NOTE]
> **Automatic vs Manual Indexes:**
> Unique constraints defined on Mongoose schemas (such as `username` on `User`, `email` on `User`, and `inviteToken` on `Group`) already generate unique database indexes automatically in MongoDB. This plan focuses strictly on unindexed foreign keys and sorting queries.

